titleproper.value:
Guide to the Rudolph Valuch Photograph Collection
          <num>ALBA.PHOTO.142</num>

author.value: Collection processed by Processed by Processed by: Evan Daniel, 2004

publisher.value: Tamiment Library and Robert F. Wagner Labor Archives

corpname.value: Tamiment Library and Robert F. Wagner Labor Archives

abstract.value:
Rudolph (Rudy) Valuch (1916[?]- ) was
        an apprentice tool and die maker affiliated with the Internatinal Association of Machinists.
        Valuch was attached to the 15th Transport Regiment of the International Brigades during the
        Spanish Civil War. The collection consists of photographic prints of the 15th Transport
        Regiment in Spain from April 1937 to September 1938 and contains group photographs and
        portraits of members of the Abraham Lincoln Brigade, Spanish troops, various military
        vehicles—motorcycles, tanks, trucks, planes—and street scenes.

p.value:
Materials are open to researchers. Please contact the Tamiment Library & Robert F.
        Wagner Labor Archives for more information and to schedule an appointment,
        tamiment.wagner@nyu.edu or 212-998-2630.

Published citations should take the following form: <lb/><lb/>Identification of item, date;
        Collection name; Collection number; box number; folder number; <lb/>Tamiment Library/Robert
        F. Wagner Labor Archives <lb/>Elmer Holmes Bobst Library <lb/>70 Washington Square South
        <lb/>New York, NY 10012, New York University Libraries.

Valuch procured the majority of the images from the photographer Charles L. Kaufman. When
        the collection was donated to ALBA, Valuch provided a numbered inventory with captions that
        corresponded to 28 of the 111 prints. The collection is arranged in one series,
        alphabetically by topic. All of the photographs were taken in Spain.

The photographic prints contain four numbers separated by colons. The first number refers
        to the collection number, the second to the box number, the third to the folder number, and
        the fourth to the individual print. For example, the first print in this collection is
        labeled 142:1:1:1.
